solution:
The area of the larger semicircle is \[
\frac{1}{2}\pi \cdot (2)^2 = 2\pi.
\] The region deleted from the larger semicircle consists of five congruent sectors and two equilateral triangles. The area of each of the sectors is \[
\frac{1}{6}\pi \cdot (1)^2 = \frac{\pi}{6}
\] and the area of each triangle is \[
\frac{1}{2}\cdot 1\cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4},
\] so the area of the shaded region is \[
2\pi - 5\cdot\frac{\pi}{6}-2\cdot\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} = \boxed{\frac{7}{6}\pi - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}.
\] [asy]
fill((0,2)..(2,0)--(-2,0)..cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((-1,1)..(0,0)--(-2,0)..cycle,white);
fill((1,1)..(0,0)--(2,0)..cycle,white);
fill((0,1)..(1,0)--(-1,0)..cycle,white);
draw((0,1)..(1,0)--(-1,0)..cycle,dashed);
draw((0,2)..(2,0)--(-2,0)..cycle);
label("$A$",(-2,0),W);
label("$B$",(2,0),E);
label("1",(-1.5,0),S);
label("1",(-0.5,0),S);
label("1",(0.5,0),S);
draw((-1.5,0.87)--(-1,0)--(-0.5,0.87)--(0,0)--(0.5,0.87)--(1,0)--(1.5,0.87),linewidth(0.7));
label("1",(1.5,0),S);
dot((0,0));
dot((-1,0));
dot((1,0));
draw((-2,-0.1)--(-2,-0.4));
draw((-1,-0.1)--(-1,-0.4));
draw((2,-0.1)--(2,-0.4));
draw((1,-0.1)--(1,-0.4));
draw((0,-0.1)--(0,-0.4));
[/asy]

We will calculate the area of the hexagon in two different ways.  Let the interior point in the figure be called $P$, and let $s$ be the side length of the hexagon. The areas of the triangles $APB$, $BPC$, $CPD$, $DPE$, $EPF$, and $FPA$ are $\frac{1}{2}(s)(4)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(6)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(9)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(10)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(8)$, and $\frac{1}{2}(s)(5)$, respectively.  Also, the area of a regular hexagon with side length $s$ is $3s^2\sqrt{3}/2$.  Setting the sum of the triangles' areas equal to $3s^2\sqrt{3}/2$ gives \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2}s(4 + 6 + 9 + 10 + 8 + 5)&=\frac{3s^2\sqrt{3}}{2} \implies \\
21s&=\frac{3s^2\sqrt{3}}{2} \implies \\
14s &= s^2\sqrt{3} \implies \\
s=0 \quad \text{or} \quad s &= \frac{14}{\sqrt{3}} \\
&= \frac{14}{\sqrt{3}}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3}}=\boxed{\frac{14\sqrt{3}}{3}} \text{ cm}.
\end{align*}[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, P, U, V, W, X, Y, Z;

A = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(60);
B = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(120);
C = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(180);
D = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(240);
E = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(300);
F = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(360);
P = extension(A + (0,-4), B + (0,-4), A + 5*dir(210), F + 5*dir(210));

U = (P + reflect(A,B)*(P))/2;
V = (P + reflect(B,C)*(P))/2;
W = (P + reflect(C,D)*(P))/2;
X = (P + reflect(D,E)*(P))/2;
Y = (P + reflect(E,F)*(P))/2;
Z = (P + reflect(F,A)*(P))/2;

draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--cycle);
draw(U--X,dotted);
draw(V--Y,dotted);
draw(W--Z,dotted);
draw(A--P);
draw(B--P);
draw(C--P);
draw(D--P);
draw(E--P);
draw(F--P);

label("$A$", A, dir(60));
label("$B$", B, dir(120));
label("$C$", C, dir(180));
label("$D$", D, dir(240));
label("$E$", E, dir(300));
label("$F$", F, dir(360));
label("$P$", P, SW, UnFill);
label("$4$", (P + U)/2, dir(180));
label("$6$", (P + V)/2, SW);
label("$9$", (P + W)/2, SE);
label("$10$", (P + X)/2, dir(180));
label("$8$", (P + Y)/2, SW);
label("$5$", (P + Z)/2, SE);
[/asy]

First note that $FE = (AB + DC)/2$. Because trapezoids $ABEF$ and $FECD$ have the same height, the ratio of their areas is equal to the ratio of the averages of their parallel sides. Since \[
AB + \frac{AB+DC}{2} = \frac{3 AB + DC}{2}
\]and \[
\frac{AB+DC}{2} + DC = \frac{AB + 3 DC}{2},
\]we have \[
3AB + DC = 2(AB + 3DC) = 2AB + 6DC, \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{AB}{DC} = \boxed{5}.
\][asy]
